                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <head>No. 269.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Outrey</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Evarts</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of France</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1880-11-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 8, 1880</date>. (Received November
                        8.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: The minister of foreign
                    affairs telegraphs to me that the Submarine Cable Company, whose line connects
                    France with the United States, asks to be authorized to make with the English
                    company arrangements which would constitute a kind of fusion. Before adopting a
                    decision my government would be glad to know what are the intentions of the
                    Government of the United States. I should, therefore, be greatly obliged to you,
                    Mr. Secretary of State, if you would have the kindness to let me know what are
                    your views on this subject, and to inform me how you will receive a similar
                    request when it shall be presented to you.</p>
                <p>Be pleased to Accept, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>MAX OUTREY.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
